<TEXT>
a jury found a blood bank negligent thursday 
for improperly screening its blood in the case of a 5yearold boy 
who contracted aids through a transfusion a verdict believed to be 
the first of its kind lawyers said 
we just feel this is a great moral victory i think the blood 
industry particularly in highrisk areas like san francisco has 
got to shape up said mary osborn whose son michael was the 
plaintiff in the case 
michael who has a brain tumor and lymphoma was diagnosed with 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome in september 1987 he has only a 
few months to live said the osborns lawyer michael moriarty 
at least michael will be around in some way in the future at 
least his name will not be forgotten added mrs osborn 
the jury found irwin memorial blood bank of san francisco which 
supplies blood to about 40 hospitals to be negligent in failing to 
screen the blood adequately although some aids screening was done 
at the facility at the time 
in addition the jury ruled that the blood bank erred in not 
allowing family members to target their blood donations for michael 
moriarty said the blood bank had rejected requests by the boys 
family and friends to donate blood for the transfusion saying they 
had no policy to accommodate such requests when in fact they did 
the blood banks attorney duncan barr denied that the blood 
bank acted negligently and said the decision will be appealed 
the jury awarded the sacramento family 550000 in compensatory 
damages the child suffering from a congenital heart defect 
received the transfusion feb 24 1983 when he was three weeks old 
the boys parents were awarded 200000 to pay for past and future 
medical bills but were denied any damages for pain and suffering 
the jury voted unanimously to award the damages and split 93 on 
the question of liability said moriarty 
defending irwins decisions in the case barr said in 1983 the 
blood bank had a policy of allowing socalled directed donors only 
for medical reasons such as blood donations from organ donors 
barr and dr thomas asher founder and chairman of hemacare 
corp a private blood bank in sherman oaks said the case was the 
first time a blood bank was found responsible for a 
transfusionrelated aids case 
a denver jury in june cleared a blood bank of liability in the 
case of a woman who contracted aids through a transfusion a similar 
case in california in 1986 ended in a settlement before the trial 
ended 
aids is caused by a virus that damages the bodys immune system 
leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer it is spread 
most often through sexual contact needles or syringes shared by 
drug abusers infected blood or blood products and from pregnant 
women to their offspring 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

