<TEXT>
wally m schirra one of the first seven 
mercury astronauts says the united states no longer leads the world 
in space technology and should renew its commitment to space 
exploration 
in an address at the us naval academy tuesday night the former 
navy captain called on the bush administration to make building a 
space station the top priority of americas space program 
such a station could serve as a port for manned and unmanned 
exploratory missions to other planets and their moons said schirra 
65 
schirra a 1946 academy graduate who is now a business executive 
wore a beat army pin the same message he carried on a placard 
during a 1965 gemini mission the annual armynavy football game is 
this weekend 
schirra said the skylab project marked the beginning of the 
decline of the us space program budget cuts forced the national 
aeronautics and space administration to allow skylab to break up in 
orbit and no serious financial commitment has been made since he 
said 
the former astronaut speaking on the eve of the launching of the 
secret military shuttle atlantis said space shuttle missions have 
had no place to go they were just supposed to go into outer 
space and come home we did that 25 years ago 
schirra praised the soviet unions space program for its 
longrange goals the soviets have done extensive research on how 
weightlessness affects humans and have worked to develop ships that 
can stay in orbit for years but the united states has attempted 
neither he said 
schirra was selected as a mercury astronaut in april 1959 in 
1962 he became the fifth astronaut to fly in space 
</TEXT>
