<TEXT>
thirdgrader victoria kennedy told her 
classmates in a hushed voice how her grandmother looked at wedding 
pictures and could not remember the names of her own family members 
matthew ouelette another westport elementary school pupil 
recalled how his neighbor an elderly woman forgot how to 
drive and forgot how to cook 
like practically everyone in their coastal town of 1850 
residents the pupils were talking about alzheimers disease as part 
of a daylong series of events wednesday put together by educators 
doctors and a drug company 
this is a test to see how much you can educate an entire town 
in one day said william connolly of new jerseybased sandoz 
pharmaceuticals corp 
the program used coloring books a mascot dog and movies to show 
how the debilitating ailment can be battled for a few hours the 
students put aside their reading writing and arithmetic to look at 
a disease that may not afflict them for 60 years if at all 
the children wanted to know how alzheimers disease gets started 
and as it happens that was one question that could not be answered 
definitively 
the purpose of the effort was not so much to understand how the 
disease works but to show how the loved ones of an alzheimers 
sufferer can with patience helpful advice and love minimize the 
worst of the diseases effects 
westport which is in the third year of a federal health and 
human services grant intended to promote community programs 
developed the alzheimers effort in meetings between school 
officials and connolly who spends summers here sandoz manufactures 
hydergine a drug that can ease some symptoms of alzheimers in 
milder cases 
for adults wednesdays program included discussions on 
positive approaches to aging a film titled there were times 
dear dramatizing a family coping with alzheimers and a lecture 
by dr william gershell a specialist in geriatrics at mount sinai 
medical center in new york city 
alzheimers afflicts an estimated 5 million mostly elderly 
americans efforts are expanding to help them cope until recently 
the focus was on patients not their families 
westport is changing that emphasis because of mounting evidence 
that children are often acutely aware of and confused by the decline 
of a loved one 
a coloring book titled helping grandma by westport high 
school art teacher betsey macdonald told the story of a grandmother 
who gradually begins to show signs of memory loss 
children are often kept in the dark about aging said 
macdonald they automatically think that old means sick but 
children are wonderfully resilient and surprisingly insightful when 
spoken to directly on the subject 
the point of the coloring book geared toward elementary school 
children is to teach them understanding and to teach them that 
what she needs is support 
connolly said a key problem with the disease is the failure to 
recognize that it is a problem 
the feeling is that to be old is to be sick and to be old is to 
be confused connolly said children ask what is wrong with an 
elderly relative and parents say well grandmas getting old 
thats not true 
one of the first things relatives can do for those showing signs 
of memory loss or other dementia is encourage them to go to a doctor 
also mature wellbehaved dogs from an animal shelter can 
provide some stability and love for an alzheimers sufferer 
connolly said jeff a black and white mongrel from a rhode island 
animal shelter has become the national poster dog for the socalled 
humananimal bonding campaign and he travels with connolly to 
events on the subject 
