<DOCNO> AP881201-0041 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
people who wear hats and sunglasses to protect 
their eyes from strong sunshine could substantially reduce the risk 
of cataracts says the author of a study published today 
the research conducted on fishermen found that frequent 
exposure to intense sun tripled the risk of a common form of 
cataracts strengthening the widely held suspicion that too much sun 
is bad for the eyes just as it is for the skin 
if there is enough sunshine for you to get sunburned then you 
should be protecting your eyes said dr hugh r taylor of johns 
hopkins university 
he noted that many people have gotten used to smearing sunblock 
on their faces to prevent skin cancer but they leave their eyes 
exposed to damaging ultraviolet light the invisible portion of the 
sunbeam that burns the skin and slowly clouds the lens of the eyes 
taylor said the easiest way to protect the eyes is to put on a 
hat with a brim 
that will cut uv exposure to the eye by 50 percent and if you 
get sunglasses you can eliminate all ocular uv exposure or cut it 
down by 80 percent to 90 percent he said in an interview 
cataracts are a common health problem resulting in more than 1 
million operations in the united states each year 
taylor and colleagues estimated the annual ultraviolet exposures 
of 838 chesapeake bay watermen who work on boats these varied 
depending on how much they fished the time of year they were on the 
water and whether they wore hats and glasses among other factors 
doctors found no association between sunlight and cataracts of 
the nucleus of the lens however they found that it was strongly 
associated with cataracts of the surrounding cortex of the lens 
cortical and nuclear cataracts each account for about onethird 
of all cases that require surgery not enough fishermen in the study 
had a third variety of eye damage known as posterior subcapsular 
cataracts to determine whether they also are caused by sunlight 
the study published in the new england journal of medicine 
found that the higher the mens exposure to ultraviolet light the 
greater their risk of cortical cataracts 
the researchers divided the watermen into four groups depending 
on the intensity of their exposure the quarter with the highest 
annual exposure had three times the risk of those in the group with 
the lowest exposure 
the research showed that people who got cortical cataracts 
received on average 21 percent more ultraviolet light than those 
who did not doubling the annual ultraviolet exposure increased the 
cataract risk by 60 percent 
in an accompanying editorial dr sidney lerman of new york 
medical college wrote that prevention of light damage to the eye 
is the best and simplest approach to the problem 
taylor said that all glasses including ordinary reading glasses 
cut exposure significantly although they vary in effectiveness the 
best are plastic lenses specifically designed to block ultraviolet 
rays these can stop virtually all of these rays from reaching the 
eyes 
he said that ordinary untinted glass spectacles stop about 80 
percent of ultraviolet radiation while similar plastic lenses keep 
out 90 percent runofthemill cheap sunglasses block about 95 
percent 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

