<TEXT>
cospeakers cochairmen cooperation thats 
the plan for the restructured indiana house its leaders say 
the house split 5050 between democrats and republicans elected 
cospeakers for the first time wednesday and adopted a special 
agreement that redistributes many of the speakers powers to the 
chambers members 
democrat michael k phillips and republican paul s mannweiler 
were named cospeakers by unanimous voice votes in the house which 
went from a 5248 gop majority to an even split after the democrats 
picked up two seats in the nov 8 election 
the two men who negotiated the powersharing agreement over 2 
days last week jointly clutched the house gavel and raised it aloft 
as the membership stood cheering and applauding 
this is a historic occasion one in which we all can take a 
great deal of pride said mannweiler who presided alone as house 
speaker the last two years 
the two men will preside over the chamber on alternate days 
phillips went first wielding the gavel after the speaker election 
mannweiler will get his turn when the house reconvenes jan 4 
the house minority leader for the last 12 years phillips quoted 
poet robert frost in a speech urging conciliation not 
confrontation during the 1989 session 
were taking the road less traveled by and that will make all 
the difference he said im convinced the system will work 
the cospeaker arrangement and a series of rules changes were 
negotiated after the house tried unsuccessfully last week to elect a 
speaker 
under the agreement each committee will have republican and 
democratic cochairmen and equal membership from each party 
the gop speaker will appoint committee members from his party and 
assign republicanauthored bills to committee the democratic 
speaker will do the same for his party 
if a cochairman does not want to hold a hearing on a bill his 
counterpart from the other party can draw on his allotment of wild 
cards to keep the bill moving 
a tie vote in a committee will send a bill to the floor without 
recommendation previously a bill died if it did not win a majority 
vote in committee 
once a bill reaches the house floor the author can control when 
it is called down for amendment and a final vote formerly the 
speaker controlled the house calendar of bills and exercised his 
greatest power by killing bills through refusing to call them for 
votes 
