<TEXT>
after three years investigating the worst 
singleplane crash in history police on thursday sought criminal 
charges against employees of the aircraft maker airline and japans 
ministry of transport 
police said the crash that killed 520 people was caused by 
professional negligence of 20 people including four boeing co 
employees japan air lines employees and four from the transport 
ministry 
they were responsible for aircraft repairs maintenance and 
inspection 
the seattlebased aircraft manufacturer thursday rejected the 
report and denied japanese charges it hindered the investigation 
gunma prefectural police handed results of the probe to the 
maebashi district prosecutors office which will decide whether to 
press charges for negligence a criminal offense in japan 
police said they were unable to question the four boeing 
employees 
but they said documents confiscated from japan air lines provided 
enough evidence to substantiate their involvement the four 
reportedly supervised a faulty repair of the aircraft in 1978 but 
have refused repeated police requests for interviews 
the boeing 747 plowed into a mountain during a flight from tokyo 
to osaka on aug 12 1985 killing all but four people aboard 
japan is one of a few countries in which criminal charges are 
sought against people responsible for airplane accidents said 
hiroshi itakura criminal law professor at tokyos nihon university 
the most important thing in an accident like this is to 
pinpoint the cause of the accident rather than to prosecute 
individuals said itakura but unlike the united states under 
japanese criminal law corporations cannot be charged for 
wrongdoing 
japan air lines president susumu yamachi said his company is 
taking the police report seriously 
boeing however rejected it 
boeing does not believe that criminal acts were committed by 
anyone and hopes that the district prosecutors office also will 
conclude that there was no criminal conduct the company said in a 
statement 
company sources said it planned to respond to the police inquiry 
but was unlikely to allow japanese police to question individual 
employees 
boeing has disclosed that it performed faulty repairs on the 
aircraft after a minor accident in 1978 damaged the rear bulkhead 
the metal partition that protects the pressurized cabin 
the aircraft skidded on its tail during a rough landing in 1978 
at osaka international airport and underwent major repairs 
according to jal 
a government report in 1987 concluded that improper repairs 
accelerated metal fatigue which caused the bulkhead to burst 
blowing off part of the planes tail fin and sending the jumbo jet 
out of control 
police said the accident could have been avoided if boeing had 
performed the repairs properly if japan air lines had checked 
repairs adequately and if the transport ministry had inspected the 
aircraft properly 
jal said about 70 percent of compensation claims have been 
settled the company and boeing agreed to share compensation for 
victims families and the four survivors 
