<TEXT>
agriculture secretary richard e lyng on 
thursday unveiled the governments 1989 program for rice farmers 
with a national average pricesupport level of 650 for each 100 
pounds 
that is down from a national average of 663 in 1988 
price support loans are paid by the governments commodity credit 
corp to farmers who post their crops as collateral because 
producers are free to forfeit the crops and keep the cash the 
system puts a floor under prices 
farmers must meet program requirements to qualify for federal 
subsidies 
lyng announced a required acreage reduction of 25 percent this 
represents land that farmers cannot plant and is designed to prevent 
surpluses 
he set the established target price at 1080 for each 100 
pounds down from 1115 this year 
target prices are used in calculating socalled deficiency 
payments that the government provides as income supports to 
participants in some programs 
other provisions of the rice program 
whole kernel milled rice price support rates were set at 1081 
per hundredweight for long grain and 981 for medium and short 
grain rice the broken kernel rate for all rice classes is 541 
producers who pledged 1989 crop rice as collateral for price 
support loans will not be permitted to purchase marketing 
certificates when repaying loans at the marketing loan repayment 
rate 
the discretionary inventory reduction program will not be 
implemented 
farmers may sign up for the program between dec 19 and april 14 
