<TEXT>
the us embassy has changed its policy 
and now sends staff members to monitor conditions in cambodian 
refugee camps run by the communist khmer rouge a spokesman for the 
mission said thursday 
us officials had feared previously that an embassy presence in 
the camps where human rights violations are widespread would be 
used for political propaganda sources reported the embassy said 
camp visits began in september 
american policy still is to avoid substantive contact with the 
khmer rouge which ruled cambodia in 197578 and killed hundreds of 
thousands of people it now is the largest guerrilla army fighting 
vietnamese occupation forces 
the khmer rouge controls four unaided camps in thailand near 
the cambodian border housing tens of thousands of refugees 
documented abuses include forced military portering relocation to 
dangerous areas denial of access to medical treatment and at least 
two executions this year 
we began these visits solely because of our humanitarian 
concern for the populations of these camps embassy spokesman ross 
petzing said we have made these visits only when representatives 
of international organizations are present our visits are solely to 
monitor conditions in the camps and are conducted by officers of the 
embassys refugee section 
petzing said embassy representatives had made about five visits 
shepard lowman director of the state departments vietnam 
cambodia and laos desk until last december said the us government 
didnt make much of an effort before to find out about the camps 
you didnt think about a return to power of the khmer rouge 
because you were dealing with a stalemate he said in an interview 
thursday as people became more convinced a settlement is possible 
the khmer rouge question is very critical 
it is thailand and thai sovereignty involved its a thai 
decision we should encourage the thais though to increasingly 
press for greater access to those camps to ensure the people are 
treated in a humanitarian way 
i think it is in the thai national interest to avoid a return 
to power of the khmer rouge 
lowman is president of a refugees international a voluntary 
agency based in washington 
on nov 25 the state department condemned forced relocations of 
civilians from the ta luan camp 
international relief officials said about 7000 refugees were 
moved from ta luan to khao phlu a heavily mined malarial jungle 
along the frontier and thousands of others were moved out of otrao 
relief officials said the guerrillas apparently planned to use 
them to populate areas in cambodia from which vietnamese troops have 
withdrawn 
the new sites have been shelled this month from inside cambodia 
forcing 30005000 people back to ta luan a relief official who 
visited the camp recently said many returned on foot carrying their 
belongings in backpacks 
they were all digging shelters at ta luan he said they 
were afraid ta luan also would come under attack 
on tuesday the khmer rouge radio denied relocating anyone by 
force and said it had not forced refugees to work as porters it 
broadcast an open letter from a group of refugees in khmer rouge 
camps saying they were performing a voluntary patriotic duty to hlp 
liberate cambodia 
people who escaped say all except elderly people and pregnant 
women were forced to fight or walk through mined forests carrying 
rice weapons ammunition and other supplies to the front lines 
inside cambodia 
those who refused were jailed in harsh conditions sometimes in 
underground prisons with little food and their ankles shackled to 
posts they said in recent interviews with visiting reporters 
