<TEXT>
a man who spent five days stranded in the 
never summer mountains and watched his friend die in his arms said 
thursday he never really panicked but just concentrated on 
staying alive 
wondering what was going to happen next was the biggest 
thing said jim edson 38 speaking from his hospital bed at st 
anthonys medical clinic in granby where he was listed in good 
condition 
edson and ray owens 66 last friday embarked on what they 
expected would be a relaxing afternoon snowmobiling in the woods 
they took a wrong turn and their snowmobiles got bogged down in a 
snowchoked gulch 16 miles northwest of grand lake edson said 
the exertion of trying to climb out of the gulch caused owens to 
have a heart attack edson said he died sunday 
edson waded out of the heavily wooded snowwhipped mountains 
some 50 miles northwest of denver on wednesday exhausted and with 
his face blackened by campfire smoke but otherwise in surprisingly 
good condition 
once ray died i knew that i was on my own he said its 
hard when your best friend dies in your arms there was nothing i 
could do but let him lay where he died 
authorities recovered owens body late wednesday afternoon and 
grand county coroner dave schoenfeld said thursday his preliminary 
examination of owens body indicates exactly what his partner said 
happened to him he said an autopsy would be completed late friday 
edson said owens suffered his first chest pains friday and that 
he took him down to the gulch and built a fire and makeshift 
shelter edson said he used gasoline and a sparkplug from the mired 
snowmobiles to light fires since he had no matches 
we couldnt get back up the way we came down edson said 
we went down a little further hoping wed come out on a trail 
but we didnt 
on saturday the men slept a lot and ate the trail mix salami 
cheese crackers and fruit they had brought with them edson said 
on sunday they heard searchers snowmobiles and an airplane and 
began burning green boughs in an effort to attract rescuers 
but blinding snow and whiteout conditions made the smoke signal 
useless and edson said he felt frustration that we didnt get 
their attention but elation knowing they were looking for us 
edson said the men then decided to strike out on their own but 
the exertion proved too much for owens 
he said lets go real slow but we didnt get more than 15 
feet from the camp and he decided he wasnt going edson said 
hes gone but i have hopes of seeing him again said edson 
who was an elder with owens at a jehovahs witnesses church in 
federal heights 
during edsons five days in the woods temperatures were below 
zero and freezing winds sent windchill factors to minus 30 degrees 
the search was called off tuesday night 
edson stayed with his friends body until wednesday hoping 
rescuers would find him he said owens was the one familiar with the 
area and he was lost once owens died 
edson said he spent his time praying and thinking about the 
weather the rescue effort and whether his contact lenses would hold 
out 
edson said he began walking about 7 am wednesday he ran across 
snowmobile tracks indicating searchers had been less than two miles 
from his campfire at about 2 pm he ran into logger tony winter 
it felt just grand edson said 
edson said winter must have thought i was a ghost i couldnt 
hardly talk i hadnt talked in two or three days i was trying to 
squeak out the words and he just said cmon around and get in the 
truck 
