<TEXT>
the most irritating thing about sundays hallmark 
hall of fame presentation on cbs the tenth man is how 
selfconsciously important it is 
based on graham greenes intriguing story of a french lawyer 
imprisoned by the nazis anthony hopkins who trades his wealth for 
his life the tenth man is tedious and overwrought as 
exemplified by the cloyingly romantic music overwhelming almost 
every scene its composed by lee holdridge who wrote the theme for 
beauty and the beast 
hopkins can be effecting in the right role but here he is merely 
irritating employing varying degrees of one emotion dumbfounded 
there is some hope when the flamboyant derek jacobi bursts on the 
scene late in the drama to add the final plot twist but by then 
its snoozing time 
the movie was shot on location in france why most of the scenes 
are interiors 
hopkins plays jean louis chavel a successful attorney with an 
estate outside paris who is accidentally picked up in a nazi sweep 
of innocent citizenry in prison he is selected as one of a random 
few every 10th prisoner to be executed in retribution against 
the resistance 
chavel tries to buy his life offering everything he has to any 
man who will take his place in front of the firing squad michel 
mangeot timothy watkins a young man with a bad cough takes him 
up on the deal so he can leave chavels wealth to his mother and 
sister 
three years later france is liberated and chavel returns to his 
mansion now in disrepair where michels mother and sister are 
living he conceals his identity and michels attractive sister 
therese kristin scott thomas hires him as a handyman she spends 
most of her spare time imagining how she will kill the hated chavel 
the plot begins to thicken when jacobi arrives claiming to be 
chavel but hes mostly lost in the headlong rush to the 
inexplicable conclusion 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
hal dabney coleman and julia jane curtin have a fabulous 
